article.description:
Chris McCray scored 20 points and Maryland (No. 20 ESPN/USA Today, No. 23 AP) opened the second half with a 16-0 run to breeze past
Nicholls State 88-56 Sunday.
article.headline: McCray, Terrapins cruise past Nicholls St. by 32
article.linkText: McCray, Terrapins cruise past Nicholls St. by 32
article.story: COLLEGE PARK, Md. (AP) -- Chris McCray scored 20 points and Maryland (No. 20 ESPN/USA Today, No. 23 AP) opened the second half with a 16-0 run to breeze past Nicholls State 88-56 Sunday. Two days after returning from Hawaii, where they played three games in less than 48 hours at the Maui Invitational, the Terrapins (4-1) endured a sluggish first half before pulling away. Ekene Ibekwe scored nine points and James Gist had two baskets in the decisive 16-point run, which gave Maryland a 55-30 lead. The margin swelled to 31 points with 10 minutes left. The Terrapins had only eight turnovers, three after halftime. McCray sank all three of his 3-point tries in the second half. It's the third time in five games he's led the Terps in scoring. Nik Caner-Medley scored 16 points, Ibekwe finished with 15 and D.J. Strawberry had 12 points and a career-high 12 assists in the Terrapins' 23rd straight non-conference home win. That streak will be tested Wednesday, when Maryland hosts Minnesota in the ACC-Big 10 Challenge. Stefan Blaszczynski led Nicholls State (1-4) with 20 points and Ryan Bathie had 12 on 4-for-7 shooting from beyond the arc. The Colonels were playing in their fourth game in seven days, and it showed in the second half. Nicholls State scored only 26 points after halftime and committed four turnovers during Maryland's 16-0 run. Caner-Medley and McCray each scored 11 points to stake the Terrapins to a 39-30 halftime lead. Maryland made eight of its first 13 shots for an 18-7 lead, but Bathie hit a pair of 3-pointers in an 8-0 spurt that got the Colonels to 31-24. Strawberry then made a 13-footer and McCray added a layup for an 11-point lead. Nicholls State had 11 turnovers and 11 baskets before halftime.
